{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657555"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20576"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20576"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.89,0.04,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93700"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13453"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76910"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12502"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32119"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93700"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAtherosclerosis is a progressive disease of the arterial wall that underlies many cardiovascular conditions. Understanding its pathogenesis is essential for developing preventive and therapeutic strategies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the initial event in the pathogenesis of atherosclerosis according to the response to injury hypothesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Smooth muscle cell migration to the intima","Endothelial cell injury","Macrophage transformation into foam cells","Platelet aggregation and thrombus formation","Calcification of the arterial wall"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the response to injury hypothesis, \u003Cstrong\u003Eendothelial cell injury\u003C/strong\u003E is the initial event in atherosclerosis pathogenesis. This injury can be caused by various factors including hypertension, smoking, hyperlipidaemia, diabetes, and inflammatory mediators. The damaged endothelium becomes dysfunctional, leading to increased permeability, expression of adhesion molecules, and recruitment of inflammatory cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent events that occur later in the atherosclerotic process:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmooth muscle cell migration to the intima\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after endothelial injury and inflammatory cell recruitment. Smooth muscle cells migrate from the media to the intima in response to growth factors and contribute to plaque formation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMacrophage transformation into foam cells\u003C/strong\u003E happens after monocytes have been recruited to the site of injury, differentiated into macrophages, and ingested oxidized low-density lipoproteins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet aggregation and thrombus formation\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in advanced lesions when the fibrous cap ruptures, exposing thrombogenic material to the bloodstream.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcification of the arterial wall\u003C/strong\u003E is a late event in atherosclerosis, associated with advanced plaques and involving osteogenic transformation of vascular smooth muscle cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing endothelial injury, the subsequent steps in atherosclerosis development include: accumulation of lipoproteins (particularly low-density lipoproteins) in the vessel wall, oxidation of these lipoproteins, recruitment of monocytes that differentiate into macrophages, formation of foam cells, release of inflammatory mediators, and proliferation of smooth muscle cells. This cascade of events represents the chronic inflammatory and healing response that characterizes atherosclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Atherosclerosis begins with endothelial injury followed by accumulation of lipoproteins in the vessel wall.","Macrophages ingest oxidized low-density lipoproteins to form foam cells, which are characteristic of early atherosclerotic lesions.","The response to injury hypothesis describes atherosclerosis as a chronic inflammatory process involving interactions between lipoproteins, immune cells, and vascular wall components."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotan Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 11; pages 494"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76910"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20576"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76910"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T08:49:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T08:50:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13453"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93700"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attri